==English==

===Etymology===
From Middle English '''worm''' < Old English '''[[wyrm]]''' (serpent, dragon, worm) < Proto-Germanic '''[[*wurmiz]]''' < Proto-Indo-European '''[[*wrmi-]]'''/'''[[*wrmo-]]''' (serpent, scorpion, maggot, worm), possibly from PIE base '''[[*wer-]]''' (to turn).

===Pronunciation===
* ''[[RP]]:'' {{IPA|/wɜːm/}}, {{SAMPA|/w3:m/}}
* ''US:'' {{AHD|wûrm}}, {{IPA|/wɝm/}}, {{SAMPA|/w3`m/}}
*{{audio|en-us-worm.ogg|Audio (US)}}
*:'''Rhymes''': [[Rhymes:English:-ɜː(r)m|-ɜː(r)m]]

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A generally [[tubular]] [[invertebrate]] of the [[annelid]] [[phylum]].
# A [[contemptible]] or [[devious]] being.
#: ''Don't try to run away, you little worm!''
# {{computing}} A [[self-replicating program]] that [[propagate]]s widely through a [[network]].
# {{cricket}} A [[graphical]] [[representation]] of the [[total]] [[run]]s [[score]]d in an [[innings]].
# Something [[spiral]], especially the [[thread]] of a [[screw]].
# {{archaic}} A [[dragon]] or [[mythological]] [[serpent]].
# An [[internal]] [[tormentor]]; something that [[gnaw]]s or [[afflict]]s one's mind with [[remorse]].
#* [[w:Shakespeare|William Shakespeare]] &mdash; The '''worm''' of conscience still begnaw thy soul!

